projects.description:
European schools struggle with a fast-changing socio-economical environment and challenges of the exponential improvement of digitalisation and its impact on the pupils' life. Amongst these circumstances, those skills and competencies are highlighted as what makes students adapt to society's needs and the labour market. The young generation faces a fast-changing environment and unpredictable challenges, but at the same time, well-known life crises also appear during the teenage years. They need to make choices every day and make decisions that sometimes significantly influence their lives. Choosing a career path, future profession, or only a sport- or free time activity needs background knowledge and a kind of structured thinking that demands many skills, what we define as life-management skills.
Our initiation aims to assist pupils through the support of schools, teachers, and parents to improve students' life management skills to achieve optimal results. We find it essential to focus on career choice as a critical factor and prepare students and parents for that difficult phase of life.

Project goals are:
Helping teachers to transform traditional teaching using more creatíve and innovatíve methods (e.g.project-based, inquiry-based, problem-based, work-based, flipped classroom methods);
Teacher competencies to embrace the potential of Open Educational Resources (OERs) within the rapid development of short up-skilling training;
Fostering creativity and entrepreneurship in education and enhancing the continuing professional development of the teaching staff;
Strengthening the ability of teachers to collaborate effectively, both inside and outside the school;
Enhancing the responsibility of students for their learning performance and learning processes;
Development of 21st-century skills and key competencies of students;

The main aim of the Erasmus+ for Security (E4S) project is to improve safety and security students’ and staff members’ as well as stakeholders dealing with refugees and/or immigrants ability to interact with customers from different cultures.

The E4S project aims to
- Improve and increase multicultural competence among teachers and staff working in the private security sector and in immigration services;
- Increase background knowledge of refugee crisis among teachers and staff in the security sector from which also the authorities can benefit;
- Produce training material on these topics by sharing experiences and best practices between participating countries related to multiculturalism, pedagogy and comparing curricula;
- Raise awareness on birth mechanisms of extremism.

E4S project seeks to meet this existing need by developing a teaching/training material package “Interacting with Multicultural Customers in Security”. The core idea of the project is that consortium of colleges and working life partners develop pedagogical methods and content for the vocational upper secondary qualification in safety and security or uniformed services pending on the partner country). 
In Finland, the content will be embedded into ‘International Security Operations’ module in Vocational Qualification in Safety and Security.
This will be achieved by further developing the already existing materials and international activities of the colleges that are part of the project consortium. The materials finished within the project’s lifecycle were piloted by partners and tested by students and company staff in in-service-training. 
The material was assessed by public authorities such as the Finnish Immigration Service and private security companies such as Securitas. Local and/or regional security companies also contributed to the project by helping to develop the contents of the modules or by sending their staff to the transnational meeting and/or staff training workshops.

profile_positions.description:
As the head of the vocational education in the school centre, I was responsible for
- the curriculum on the school level;
- the development of practical and theoretical education;
- the production units of the school's workshops: production planning, procurement processes, sales and marketing processes, resource management, innovation management projects (7 units with 130 colleagues);
The main parts of my work were cooperation 
- with other training organisations;
- with the Ministry of Agriculture;
- with the education service providers;
- and with the companies related to our vocational field. 
I organised and coordinated the assessments in daily work, supported teachers in every part of their job, and coordinated creating and implementing strategic plans to develop the learning process.

I focused on international work, motivated teachers and students to get experience abroad, and helped them compile and realise international programs in the mobility and strategical partnerships frameworks. 
I managed Hungary's most complex mobility project with 161 people to 14 different work fields and venues in 2014-2016.
